comments.body:
This benchmark doesn't re-use memory (add to freelist then remove from freelist); maybe it would be better if it did because that's what happens with the real coins cache, maybe something like this:

<details>
<summary>patch</summary>

```diff
-    size_t batch_size = 5000;
+    // The steady-state size of the map will be half of this value;
+    // power-of-2 to avoid expensive mod operation during benchmark.
+    constexpr size_t batch_size = 1 << 13;
 
     // make sure each iteration of the benchmark contains exactly 5000 inserts and one clear.
     // do this at least 10 times so we get reasonable accurate results
 
     bench.batch(batch_size).minEpochIterations(10).run([&] {
         auto rng = ankerl::nanobench::Rng(1234);
-        for (size_t i = 0; i < batch_size; ++i) {
-            map[rng()];
+        for (size_t i = 0; i < batch_size * 10; ++i) {
+            uint64_t r{rng()};
+            // if the map has few entries, more likely add an entry, else delete
+            if ((r & (batch_size-1)) < map.size()) {
+                map.erase(map.begin());
+            } else {
+                map[r];
+            }
         }
         map.clear();
     });
```
</details>

I don't think it matters which entry we delete, since `map.begin()` could return any entry. Deleting a truly random entry gets more complicated, and I don't think it changes the performance significantly. The loop iterates `batch_size * 10` instead of `batch_size` so we reach steady-state (about equal numbers of insertions and deletions).

